Course Summary

The state of Oregon is now using the National Evaluation Series (NES) English Language Arts (ELA) exam for the ORELA ELA test. The study resources in this course include short and engaging video lessons and quizzes to help you prepare for the ORELA ELA exam. They will help jog your memory, and you will get the practice you need to be able to answer exam questions with no problem.

About this Course

Here you can watch chapters full of interesting video lessons and quizzes about the structure of written works, romantic prose and poetry, and oral traditions. You can test just how well you know the techniques for comprehension, persuasive writing, and public speaking by taking our short multiple-choice quizzes. This course's collaboration of the video lessons and quizzes will give you the reassurance and practice you need. You can also use the NES English Language Arts Study Guide to prepare to help you answer test questions about the following:

  • Impact of the English language
  • How to teach students to identify word meanings, understand figures of speech, and learn new vocabulary
  • Techniques for reading comprehension
  • Structure of written works
  • Plot, theme and point of view
  • Informational texts, persuasive texts, and functional texts
  • Literary genres, including literary fiction and nonfiction
  • Ways of analyzing fiction, nonfiction, literary drama, poetry, and prose
  • Old English, Middle English, and Renaissance literature
  • Literature of the 1600s, 1700s, Romantic, Modernist, and Victorian periods
  • Oral traditions in literature
  • Conventions of grammar, comma usage, and spelling
  • Writing process and parts of research writing
  • Expository and persuasive writing
  • Techniques for public speaking
  • Critical reading and effective listening
  • Ways for interpreting visual images

About The Exam

The ORELA English Language Arts exam is taken by people who plan to obtain their teaching license in English Language Arts in the state of Oregon. The exam is computerized and offered year-round, you just have to make an appointment. You will have approximately 3 hours to answer 150 multiple-choice questions. You can determine how much time out of the total time is spent on each section of the exam.

Preparing and Registering for the ORELA English Language Arts Exam

This study guide enables you study and jog your memory in small amount of time. Plus, you can work at your own pace. Below each lesson video, there is a timeline that can help you move from one topic to the next. If you would like additional practice after taking the quizzes, you can always take the final and chapter exams. Read through the lesson transcripts to review important terms.

Registration for the ORELA English Language Arts exam can be completed online. You can also request special arrangements if needed. Registration requires a test fee. Try to register as early as possible as test appointments are filled on a first-come, first-serve basis.

Scoring the ORELA English Language Arts Exam

You must get a minimum score of 236 to pass the ORELA English Language Arts Exam. Your scores are reported to you right after you take the exam. Your full score report will be sent to you approximately two weeks after you've taken your exam. All five subsections of the exam must be completed within three hours.

Vocabulary, Reading Comprehension, and Reading Various Text Forms

Percentage of exam score: 23%

Exam topics covered: Strategies for developing vocabulary and reading comprehension, understanding and assessment of informational, persuasive, functional, and technical texts

What you'll study: In this course, you will find lessons about the historical significance of English, teaching vocabulary, word definitions including connotations and denotations, methods for reading comprehension, structural elements of different types of texts, and informational, functional, and other types of texts.

Analyzing and Interpreting Literature

Percentage of exam score: 23%

Exam topics covered: Literary analysis of different genres, including fiction and drama, interpretation of poetry, characteristics of world literature, and major historical and political aspects of different works of literature

What you'll study: This study guide will help you learn about structure, climax, theme, point of view, literary genres, analysis of literature, fiction, drama, poetry, prose, literature from the 18th century, Old English, and Romantic poetry.

English Language Conventions, Compositions, Writing Process, and Research

Percentage of exam score: 19%

Exam topics covered: Rules for Standard American English, composition, the process of writing, and research elements and standards

What you'll study: Review these lessons to cover punctuation and grammar rules, parts of speech, spelling rules, writing methods and processes, and research strategies.

Modes of Writing

Percentage of exam score: 23%

Exam topics covered: Methods for narrative, expository, persuasive, and critical writing

What you'll study: You will find lessons that will help you with narrative writing, different forms of expository writing, persuasive writing, and critical reading and writing.

Oral and Visual Communication

Percentage of exam score: 12%

Exam topics covered: Methods for effective speaking and listening, participation in group discussions, and techniques for analyzing and interpreting different types of visual media

What you'll study: The lessons in this study guide cover methods for public speaking, strategies for listening effectively and ways to interpret and present visual images.
